%N A395470 Decimal expansion of the angle theta (in radians) such that 3*theta and 2*theta are the half central angles of the circular arcs of a constructible squarable lune.
%C A395470 The angle in degrees is 26.812... . The two half central angles are 3*theta = 1.403... = 80.437... degrees, and 2*theta = 0.935... = 53.624... degrees.
%C A395470 See A395465 for details, references and more links.
%H A395470 Amiram Eldar, <a href="/A395466/a395466.png">Illustration</a>.
%H A395470 Mikhail Mikhailovich Postnikov, <a href="https://www.jstor.org/stable/2589121">The Problem of Squarable Lunes</a>, The American Mathematical Monthly, Vol. 107, No. 7 (2000), pp. 645-651. Translated from Russian by Abe Shenitzer.
%H A395470 <a href="/index/Tra#transcendental">Index entries for transcendental numbers</a>.
%F A395470 Equals arccos((sqrt(33)-1)/8)/2.
%F A395470 Equals arcsin(sqrt(9-sqrt(33))/4).
%e A395470 0.467964727830662986803279867689423001766006742525581...
%t A395470 RealDigits[ArcCos[(Sqrt[33] - 1)/8]/2, 10, 120][[1]]
%o A395470 (PARI) acos((sqrt(33)-1)/8)/2
